---
import Base from "../../../layouts/Base.astro";

const TYPE_BREAKDOWN: { label: string; count: number; max: number }[] = [
  { label: "feat", count: 38, max: 40 },
  { label: "chore", count: 34, max: 40 },
  { label: "fix", count: 24, max: 40 },
  { label: "build", count: 11, max: 40 },
  { label: "refactor", count: 9, max: 40 },
  { label: "docs", count: 9, max: 40 },
  { label: "ci", count: 5, max: 40 },
  { label: "test", count: 3, max: 40 },
  { label: "style", count: 3, max: 40 },
];

const bar = (n: number, max: number) => {
  const width = Math.round((n / max) * 32);
  return "█".repeat(width) + "·".repeat(32 - width);
};

const breakdownLines = TYPE_BREAKDOWN.map(
  (t) => `${t.label.padEnd(9, " ")}  ${bar(t.count, t.max)}  ${t.count}`,
).join("\n");
---

<Base
  title="DS-V2 contribution profile, Jeff Mills"
  description="Contribution profile across two years of platform-level work on the DS-V2 design-system monorepo. Conventional-commit type breakdown and a description of the highest-leverage changes."
>
  <p class="project-back"><a href="/projects/design-system-v2">&laquo; back to ds-v2</a></p>
  <h1 class="page-title">ds-v2 &middot; contribution profile</h1>
  <p class="project-meta">
    <span class="project-year">2022-2024</span>
    <span class="meta-sep">&middot;</span>
    <span class="project-status">~160 commits</span>
    <span class="meta-sep">&middot;</span>
    <span>platform-level work</span>
  </p>

  <p class="page-lede">
    Roughly 160 commits authored across two years of active platform work on
    the DS-V2 monorepo. Below: the conventional-commit type breakdown, then a
    description of the highest-leverage changes by category.
  </p>

  <aside class="callout">
    <span class="callout-label">Architectural overview only</span>
    <p>
      Commit hashes, diffs, and per-commit metadata stay in the private
      repository. The description below is by category, not by commit.
      Happy to walk through specifics under NDA,
      <a href="mailto:jeffy9@gmail.com">reach out</a>.
    </p>
  </aside>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <h2 class="section-title">contribution profile</h2>
  <p class="section-lede">
    Conventional-commit type breakdown across the authored set.
  </p>

  <pre class="type-chart">{breakdownLines}</pre>

  <p class="profile-note">
    The shape tells a story: heavy on <code>feat</code> and
    <code>chore</code> means the work was platform-level, not
    ticket-by-ticket. Storybook integration, monorepo plumbing, release
    tooling, lint/format hooks, the infrastructure decisions that
    let the rest of the team move.
  </p>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <h2 class="section-title">highest-leverage changes, by category</h2>

  <article class="commit-block">
    <h3 class="commit-cat">foundation</h3>
    <p class="commit-note">
      <strong>Stood up the entire monorepo.</strong> Nx with Vue 3, Vite,
      TypeScript, Storybook, and ESLint as the foundation the next two
      years of work built on. Project-tagging conventions, the cacheable
      task runner, all set up in the first week. Pre-Vite-everywhere,
      pre-Nx-default-in-Vue-shops.
    </p>
  </article>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <article class="commit-block">
    <h3 class="commit-cat">storybook with vite</h3>
    <p class="commit-note">
      Storybook landed configured with the Vite builder when the default
      everywhere else was still Webpack. The team got HMR-fast Storybook
      from day one and never had to migrate later.
    </p>
  </article>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <article class="commit-block">
    <h3 class="commit-cat">lint and format hooks</h3>
    <p class="commit-note">
      Husky, lint-staged, Prettier, and ESLint wired into the commit
      lifecycle for the whole monorepo. Code quality enforced at write
      time, not in review, the most leveraged thing a platform
      engineer can ship in the first month.
    </p>
  </article>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <article class="commit-block">
    <h3 class="commit-cat">release tooling</h3>
    <p class="commit-note">
      <code>@jscutlery/semver</code> wired into every library&rsquo;s
      Nx project, with conventional-commit parsing and per-library tag
      prefixes. Every CHANGELOG entry from that point forward is produced
      by this pipeline. Versioning becomes a derivable property of the
      commit history rather than a manual ceremony.
    </p>
  </article>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <article class="commit-block">
    <h3 class="commit-cat">css compositions</h3>
    <p class="commit-note">
      A one-line enable unlocked utility-first style primitives across the
      entire design system. Small diffs that move large abstractions are
      the senior signal in the type breakdown above, the
      <code>feat</code> count includes a lot of work that fits in one
      line.
    </p>
  </article>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <p class="project-foot">
    Back to <a href="/projects/design-system-v2">DS-V2 overview</a>
    &middot; <a href="/projects/design-system-v2/components">Component-library overview</a>
    &middot; <a href="/case-studies/02-building-the-design-system">Building the design system
    (case study)</a>
  </p>
</Base>

